howUserPublicProfile?gid=h0gfather>H0gfather</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 639<br> <font color=#333333>(10/26/02 8:37:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=387.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.aus-1.au.nu/images/photo.gif width=90 height=112></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_mad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Fix CoH or just change it to something else!</span><hr size=1> First of all, this is in reponse to a number of threads I've seen here over the past year. It is not to continue discussion on particular CoH nerfs but to propose a solution, hence its a new thread (just thought I'd stick the disclaimer in before a half-asleep mod locks the thread thinking its a duplicate).<br>
<br>
VI regrets putting Call of the Hero into the game, because like T-Rods its so powerful it continually ruins their carefully laid plans for how encounters should work. The net result is that this powerful and famous Magician spell is continually removed from entire zones. <br>
<br>
The CoH-disabled zone list is growing. Fair enough, anyone can see why they do it in zones with Ring quests and zones with areas designated for specific numbers of people.<br>
<br>
But it is an unacceptable solution. This powerful ability is crippled because it continually breaks encounters. I therefore propose two solutions:<br>
<br>
1 - Do the work necessary to make it possible to designate areas of zones that cannot be CoHed into. Its simple, simply apply a X-Y-Z range check when casting it in affected zones. It's not rocket science. The game already checks on spells for Z-axis ranges (target too far above / below you) and X-Y range (target is too far away).<br>
<br>
2 - EQ is an old lumpy game and is no doubt by now lots of spaghetti code. The above solution may simply not be possible. <br>
<br>
Fine. Remove the spell altogether, changing it to a new ability or spell line of similar merit. There is certainly no shortage of ideas, this message board alone is full of ideas to further enhance the Mage class.<br>
<br>
Having a powerful class-specific ability continually just be turned off because it pushes against the structure of encounters and breaks them just isn't a worthy option in my opinion. A large part of the Magician power curve in Kunark (as uninspiring as many would say it is) was Call of the Hero, the shining gem amongst a very mediocre expansion for Mages. <br>
<br>
It deserves to be fixed so that it no longer breaks the game but remains a useful tool, or to be replaced by a new power altogether. Simply turning it off when it causes problems should no longer be considered a feasible solution.<br>
<br>
